1. Assignment operator, functions, and subsetting

Well start with the basics: assigning values to objects using the assignment operator <-.

apple <- 5

orange <- 3

Then, we learned how to use functions in R. There are many functions out there to do the work you want!

sum(apple, orange)
## [1] 8

However, were not stuck with simple numbers! We can get more complex with our objects.

apple_weights <- c(0.3, 0.2, 0.25, 0.29)

orange_weights <- c(0.2, 0.18, 0.25, 0.24)

fruits <- c("apple", "orange", "banana", "pear", "persimmon", "grapefruit")

Then, we can subset our data using []. Lets say we want the first apple weight.

apple_weights[1]
## [1] 0.3

Now, lets say we want all the orange weights that are less than 0.24.

orange_weights[orange_weights < 0.24]
## [1] 0.20 0.18

What would you write if you wanted to get the third element in fruits?

2. More complex data

Were going to do a bit of set up by loading in our packages (aka libraries) and our data. Remember that packages are collections of functions that do specific things. Today, were using the tidyverse, which is a suite of packages all designed to make your data analysis life easier.
For something fun this time (not that urchins arent fun, we just worked with them for 3 months), were going to be using data from Tidy Tuesday, a weekly social coding event where people work to visualize data from a dataset and share on Twitter! This data was from June 2020 on marble races; check out the readme for info on the columns and what kinds of data they hold!

3. Filtering observations from a data frame and the %>% operator

We have our marbles data loaded into RStudio. Lets say we want to know the mean race time for a specific marble - maybe the one called Snowflake.

We can do this using functions and operators from the tidyverse, which is the package we loaded in.

The way we can get the mean race time for Snowflake with tidyverse functions is:
1. filter(): filter the data frame to only include observations for Snowflake
2. summarize(): calculate the mean race time

Both of these functions are from the dplyr package in the tidyverse.

We also learned how to use the pipe operator %>% from the magrittr package. This allows you to link functions together, which can be very handy! This is a pretty simple example, but we learned how powerful that operator can be (and will demonstrate later on).

snowflake_mean <- marbles %>% 
  
  filter(marble_name == "Snowflake") %>% 
  
  summarize(mean_time = mean(time_s))


snowflake_mean
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   mean_time
##       <dbl>
## 1      188.

Try finding the mean time for another marble in the data set!

We could do this for every marble in the data frame, but that would get tedious. To streamline things, we can use the group_by() function also from dplyr to tell R: think of this as a group.

all_means <- marbles %>% 
  
  group_by(marble_name) %>% 
  
  summarize(mean_time = mean(time_s))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

4. Data visualization

Now that we have our data, its time for the fun part: visualizing it!

Lets say were interested in the way that average time per lap is related to track length.

This is the most basic way to visualize it:

ggplot(data = marbles, aes(x = track_length_m, y = avg_time_lap)) +
  
  geom_point() 
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

But we can make this a lot more readable!

ggplot(data = marbles, aes(x = track_length_m, y = avg_time_lap)) +
  
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  
  geom_smooth(color = "royalblue", size = 2) +
  
  theme_bw() +
  
  labs(x = "Track length (m)",
       y = "Average time per lap (s)",
       title = "How does track length influence average time per lap?",
       caption = "Data courtesy of Thomas Mock, #TidyTuesday",
       color = "Team name") 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Ok, that was a pretty good plot. But lets say were interested in the best marble.

Well filter out observations to only include races with 1 lap. Then, well calculate the mean race time for each marble, and do some arrangement so that we can see the order better.

best_marble <- marbles %>% 
  
  filter(number_laps == 1) %>% 
  
  group_by(marble_name) %>% 
  
  summarize(mean_times = mean(time_s)) %>% 
  
  arrange(-mean_times) %>% 
  mutate(marble_name = fct_relevel(marble_name, marble_name))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

Then, we can visualize the data! Again, you could do something basic:

ggplot(data = best_marble, aes(x = marble_name, y = mean_times)) +
  
  geom_col()

Or, you could do something fun to look at!

First, well load in viridis, which is a package of color palettes to make choosing colors easier. There are tons of color palette packages out there, so lots to explore!

# if you don't have viridis yet, uncomment the line below and run it first!
# install.packages("viridis")
library(viridis)
## Loading required package: viridisLite

Then, we can plot!

ggplot(data = best_marble, aes(x = marble_name, y = mean_times)) +
  
  geom_col(aes(fill = marble_name)) +
  
  scale_y_continuous(expand = c(0, 0), limits = c(0, 35)) +
  
  scale_fill_viridis(option = "viridis", discrete = TRUE) +
  
  labs(x = "Marble name", 
       y = "Average time per lap (s)",
       title = "Which marble is the fastest?",
       subtitle = "Prim is the winner!",
       caption = "Data courtesy of Thomas Mock, #TidyTuesday") + 
  
  theme_minimal() +
  
  theme(legend.position = "none", 
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60, vjust = 0.6))
